        "content": "<p><code>simp</code> shouldn't care about axiom lists. That being said, none of these seem like they would do much as <code>simp</code> lemmas.</p>",
        "id": 486899905,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1733728554
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Your prototypical <code>simp</code> lemma looks like <code>p x = q x</code> or <code>p x iff q x</code>, where <code>q x</code> is some expression that is \"simpler\" than <code>p x</code>. For instance, <code>x ^ 2 = 0 iff x = 0</code> would make a good <code>simp</code> lemma. None of these axioms are doing anything like that.</p>",
        "id": 486902880,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1733728662
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's very useful. Thank you <span aria-label=\"thank you\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f64f\" role=\"img\" title=\"thank you\">:thank_you:</span> </p>\n<p>Is there any way in which I assume that my ten statements are true (that's what I tried to do when using the keyword <code>axiom</code>), and then use them to perform some sort of (higher-order, or whatever is possible using intelligent tactics) simplification of a certain goal?</p>",
